[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The methodological foundations are solid: fitted Q-iteration, conservative Q-learning (CQL), batch-constrained deep Q-networks, and model-based approaches have all been applied. A note on confounding: CQL's conservatism (staying close to the behavior policy) partially mitigates confounding by avoiding extrapolation to unseen state-action regions, but it does not eliminate it. The historical data still reflects selection bias in who received which doses. For stronger causal claims, consider propensity-weighted trajectories or doubly-robust estimators layered on top of the offline RL pipeline. These add computational cost but provide more defensible counterfactual estimates. The challenge is not algorithmic; it's validation. How do you prove a learned policy is safe before deploying it on patients?
